<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-689-198  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 689 198.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Transactions on Robotics and Automation  April 1989 v5 n2p151(15).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computing and controlling the compliance of a robotic hand.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cutkosky, Mark R.; Kao, Imin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Viable grasp of an object (such as a tool) by a robotic handdepends on the relative stiffness or compliance of that grasp.andO;Stiffness is shown to be a combination of compliances in thefinger tips, fingers, servo gains or laxness in the finger and armjoints, and changes in forces resulting from small changes infinger and arm geometry and contact between fingers and theobject.andP;  Understanding these factors is central to implementingrobotic tasks involving small motions and low velocities, as thedynamic equations for such operations are dominated by compliance,contact and friction functions.andP;  Equations are developed for thedetermination and control of the various force and motionrelationships in a robotic hand.andP;  The coupling of finger joints toachieve suitable gains for ensuring a desired grasp stiffness isexplored.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Robot ArmsFeedbackManipulatorsControl Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Coordinate systems for a single finger touching a grasped object.andO;(chart)Forward force/motion relationships for finger and object in figure1. (table)Typical structural compliances in the Standord/JPL hand. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>